Roberton Dataset Analysis Report
1. Introduction
The Roberton dataset contains information on 100 volunteers, capturing demographic details (age, gender, handedness), lifestyle factors (physical activity), and cognitive performance (reaction time). This report provides a structured analysis of the dataset, highlighting key trends, relationships, and insights.

2. Dataset Summary
Entries: 100

Variables: Age, Gender, Handedness, Physical Activity, Reaction Time (numeric), Reaction Time (Quick/Slow)

No missing values were detected.

Age range: 6–80 years

Physical activity range: 0.5–6.5

Reaction time range: 0.17–0.49 seconds

3. Descriptive Statistics
Variable	Mean	Std Dev	Min	Max
Age	37.26	18.64	6	80
Physical Activity	3.19	1.40	0.5	6.5
Reaction Time	0.31	0.07	0.17	0.49


4. Reaction Time Categories
Quick responders: 49 volunteers (mean = 0.257s)

Slow responders: 51 volunteers (mean = 0.365s)

This shows a clear separation between quick and slow groups.

5. Gender Differences
Females: 0.326s (slower)

Males: 0.296s (faster)

➡️ Males generally responded faster than females.

6. Handedness Differences
Left-handed (LH): 0.275s

Right-handed (RH): 0.316s

➡️ Left-handed participants had quicker reaction times.

7. Relationships Between Variables
Age vs Reaction Time: Positive correlation (0.836) → Older participants tend to respond slower.

Physical Activity vs Reaction Time: Negative correlation (-0.799) → Higher activity levels are linked to faster responses.

Age vs Physical Activity: Negative correlation (-0.684) → Older participants reported lower activity levels.

8. Key Insights
Physical activity is the strongest predictor of faster reaction times.

Age significantly slows reaction times.

Gender differences exist, with males being faster on average.

Handedness matters: left-handed individuals tend to respond quicker.

The dataset is balanced between quick and slow responders.

9. Conclusion
The Roberton dataset highlights the importance of lifestyle and biological factors in cognitive performance. Maintaining physical activity is crucial for quicker reaction times, while age, gender, and handedness also play significant roles.

